[normal]Written evidence[bold] from[bold] [bold]Fred[bold]die [bold]Talberg[bold] CEO of PIE Mapping’ (CYC0026)[bold]Executive Summary[bold]PIE mapping have been running successful
[normal]ly
[normal] a HGV complaint routing service in partnership with London Councils that gives hauliers routes to follow
[normal], 
[normal]which is 
[normal]well 
[normal]received by the industry, both domestic
[normal]ally
[normal] and with a growing number of international operators.  
[normal]PIE also developed for
[normal] the Olympics 
[normal]a Freight Journey Planner used by TFL (still in legacy) that has the capability to impose road segment restrictions by time of day.  This was used effectively by the freight industry during the Games.
[normal]As such intelligent use and sharing of the road is in o
[normal]peration for the Lorry Control Scheme and is proof that it is possible to add further time and day dependent restrictions that the industry can manage around.  
[normal]Should good quality cycle data by; location and time of day
[normal] for a
[normal] 
[normal]cycle safety restriction, 
[normal]plu
[normal]s any key 
[normal]‘left turn’
[normal] sites that are more dangerous to use at certain times 
[normal]be available. 
[normal]This data can be included into a 
[normal]viable safer freight routing scheme.  This will be a more practical app
[normal]roach than an area wide HGV ban and more effective as we learn
[normal] more about how best to de-conflict HGV’s and cyclists. 
[normal]Other recommendations that would be
[normal] effective and
[normal] easier to implement 
[normal]that will have 
[normal]a big impact is to enforce construction projects to ensure contractor vehicles meet time of day and location routi
[normal]ng criteria.  
[normal]As such we have working proof that with good data we can set up a service for compliant HGV routes.  This will enable us to share our limited road space capacity more securely and still operate the city effectively.
